Linear models as a unifying framework

We will learn the essentials

- t-tests
- regression
- analysis of variance

in the context of linear models:

\[ y = \alpha + \beta x \]

What is a model?

Models

Model: a mathematical representation of the relationship between a response variable \(y\) and one or more explanatory variables.

All models are wrong, but some are useful (George Box)

Linear models

A model is linear if \(y\) can be written as a linear function of the parameters (e.g., \(\beta\)).

Linear models

Linear

\[ \begin{aligned} y = \alpha + \beta x \\ y = \alpha + \beta_1 x + \beta_2 x^2 \\ \end{aligned} \]

Non-linear

\[ \begin{aligned} y = \alpha x^ \beta \\ y = \alpha \beta ^x \\ y = \frac{\beta_1x}{\beta_2 + x} \end{aligned} \]

Linear models

General equation for a linear model:

\[ \begin{aligned} y_i = \alpha + \sum{\beta_ix_i} + \epsilon_i \\ \epsilon_i \sim N(0, \sigma) \end{aligned} \]

Example: linear regression

Does higher plant biodiversity affect ecosystem stability?

Tilman et al. (2006) seeded 161 plots (9 x 9m) with varying numbers of plant species (1, 2, 4, 8, 16).

Plant species were assigned randomly to plots (18 possible species).

After 10 years of maintenance and measurement, researchers measured the stability of plant biomass production for each plot:

\[ \begin{aligned} \text{Biomass stability} = \frac{\bar{x}_\text{biomass}}{s_\text{biomass over 10 years}} \\ \end{aligned} \]

Load the data

# Packages
library(tidyverse)
library(broom)
theme_set(theme_bw(base_size = 14) + 
            theme(panel.grid = element_blank())) 

# Set the web address where R will look for files from this repository
repo_url <- "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/elahi/xdp/master/data/"
dat <- read_csv(paste(repo_url, 
                      "chap17e3PlantDiversityAndStabilityRaw.csv", 
                      sep = ""))
dat <- dat %>% 
  mutate(stability_log = log(biomassStability)) # natural log (base e)

Simple linear regression model

\[ \begin{aligned} \text{log(stability)} = \alpha + \beta (\text{species number}) + \epsilon \\ \end{aligned} \]

m1 <- lm(stability_log ~ nSpecies, data = dat)
tidy(m1)
## # A tibble: 2 x 5
##   term        estimate std.error statistic  p.value
##   <chr>          <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept)    3.41     0.205      16.6  1.37e-36
## 2 nSpecies       0.160    0.0243      6.62 5.32e-10

T-tests as linear models

  • one-sample t-test
  • paired t-test
  • two-sample t-test

One-sample t-test as a linear model

One number (intercept, i.e., the mean), predicts \(y\)

t.test(x = dat$stability_log)
summary(lm(stability_log ~ 1, data = dat))

One-sample t-test as a linear model

Paired t-test as a linear model

One intercept predicts the pairwise \(y_2 - y_1\) differences

## Example code; does not run
t.test(x = y2, y = y1, paired = TRUE)
summary(lm(y2 - y1 ~ 1, data = dat))

Two-sample t-test as a linear model

An intercept for group 1 (plus a difference if group 2) predicts \(y\)

## Example code; does not run
t.test(x = y2, y = y1, var.equal = TRUE)
summary(lm(y1 ~ 1 + group2, data = dat)) # ANOVA w/ two groups

Linear model for analysis of variance:

\[ \begin{aligned} y_{ij} = \mu + A_i + \epsilon_{ij} \\ \end{aligned} \]

In this case, factor A has two groups.

ANOVA as linear model: example

dat <- read_csv(paste(repo_url, "chap15e1KneesWhoSayNight.csv", 
                      sep = ""))

\[ \begin{aligned} \text{shift}_{ij} = \mu + \text{treatment}_i + \epsilon_{ij} \\ \end{aligned} \]

m0 <- lm(shift ~ 1, data = dat) # null model
m1 <- lm(shift ~ treatment, data = dat) 

tidy(m0)

Exercises

Use the following data to conduct a t-test:

cleared <- c(3.012, 1.021, 3.240, 3.613, 1.650, 4.090, 2.980)
control <- c(2.416, 0.980, 2.098, 2.346, 1.057, 2.910, 2.063)
dat <- data.frame(day = seq(1, 7, by = 1), cleared, control)
dat_long <- dat %>% gather(key = treatment, value = par, cleared:control)
t.test(par ~ treatment, data = dat_long, var.equal = TRUE)

Now use a lm() on the same data. Compare the outputs from the two analyses. Write the linear model with coefficients.

Whitlock and Schluter, Chapter 18, #2 (p 626)
